348 To Augustus. [mox n.

When, testing from long years of warsare, Greece Began to cultivate the arts of peace, And, in the sunshine of unclouded hours, Dropped from her nerveless grasp her noblest powers. On athletes now, and now on steeds she poured The fervour of her passion, now adored Statues m marble, bronze, and ivory wrought. Or pored on pictures in ecstatic thought; VVas now all mad for music, sparkling bright, Now in the grave tragedians took delight; Just like the child, who with its nurse at play Discards to-morrow what it sought to-day. Likings, dislikings, whims of mere caprice, These were the fruits of luxury and peace.

At Rome 'twas long our sashion and our pride, By dawn to be about,—fling open wide The doen—see clients, coach them in the law,— Put money. out on bonds without a flaw, And covered by good names—from reverend men To learn, and tell the younger folks again What ways were best our fortunes to amend, And curb desires that in destruction end.
